he raises the PDA toward the camera so it fills the center of attention. The device is silver and dark gray, about palm-sized, with a rectangular screen, a writing area below it, and several round physical buttons along the bottom edge. In a close-up, the screen shows a grid of small application icons, like a digital organizer’s home screen.\n\nThe woman lowers the device and looks down at it, using it as she continues speaking. Her fingers cradle the PDA while she reads from the screen. Her expression is confident and engaged, then she smiles as if finding a useful message or appointment. A moment later, her face changes to a puzzled, annoyed, or resigned look, as though the information on the device has created another obligation.\n\nThe scene cuts to a plain white background with the red COMPUSA logo centered. Under the logo, black text reads, “Where America Buys Technology.” Below that is the website, “www.compusa.com.” The final product display appears on a white background: three Palm handheld PDAs are lined up side by side, each shown front-facing with screens full of icons. Text above them reads, “Free 16 meg expansion card,” with a round Palm logo at the upper right. The models are labeled beneath the devices as “Palm m505,” “Palm m125,” and “Palm m500.” Small fine print appears along the bottom, stating that the memory is received free by mail after rebate, valid while supplies last, with store details, and an offer expiration date of 12/24/01.",
